      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
Hintae wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;2. Endurance based imitate death. Make it similar to fading memories in that sense. A bard can only fade 8-10 times before OOM and has to regen mana, it would be similar with our ID and endurance.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;3. Reduced mem-wipe time. 30 seconds is more than sufficient.&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;2.&amp;nbsp; Never gonna happen, they don't want another FM out there.&amp;nbsp; And we really don't want to have it.&amp;nbsp; We've been held back from getting stuff because of FD as well as other "perks" of our class, and bards have been held back from getting stuff because they have FM.&amp;nbsp; Can you imagine how much further we'd be kept back if we had both??&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;3. 30 seconds is WAAAY to short.&amp;nbsp; Most mobs corpse camp longer than that, and losing aggro isn't always good for pulling.&amp;nbsp; Many FD splitting techniques involve still having aggro on the mobs as they walk back.&amp;nbsp; And before you say it, the majority of the mobs who corpse camp longer than 30 seconds if you are splitting 3-4 of them, you can easily be killed in less than 1 round, so standing back up to keep aggro every 30 seconds is not an option, especially in tight spaces.&amp;nbsp; Two minute is a perfectly reasonable amount of time.&amp;nbsp; A good alternative would be a way to increase the chance to memblur and a way to raise the level cap on mobs that always memblurred by an FD.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;As an aside, I've always found kind of weird that almost all of the people who want on demand ID also want a lot shorter time for the memblur from staying FD'd.&amp;nbsp; To me it sounds kind of like, I want to be able to do what Bards can do and I want to be able to wait only a little longer and have the same result.&amp;nbsp; Personally, I don't think that either of these changes would have any impact at all on our pulling abilities, or they would only have a barely noticeable effect.&lt;/P&gt;</description>
